The Prague Stock Exchange collapsed to a minus at the end of trading
After a sharp fall in the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange corrected the losses.
Transactions with <0xC4><0x8C>EZ shares reached almost half of the normal daily trade.
The Prague Stock Exchange has been following its downturn on Monday since the start of trading on Tuesday, when it fell by almost six percent.
This time, there is a decline in Wall Street shares.
This is also reflected in the reaction of the market to the result of the vote of the US House of Representatives, which refused to support the stabilisation plan for the financial sector there.
Fall of stock in Asia
The dramatic fall on Tuesday saw stock markets in Asia, although the indexes eventually cleared some of the losses during the day.
The Hang Seng Index in Hong Kong dropped nearly four percent during trading, but later cut some of the losses and reduced the decline to around 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index, which tracks Chinese stock movements on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, fell by 3.8 percent, with markets closed in Shanghai.
Stocks on the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but eventually fell to 4.3 percent.
Taiwan’s stock market fell by 3.6 per cent, according to the index.
“The timing of the U.S. bailout is uncertain and will affect financial markets around the world,” said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority.
Hong Kong, although part of China, determines its monetary policy independently, i.e. without dependence on the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as in the United States.
U.S. lawmakers, according to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, should quickly return to negotiations and approve a proposal to support the financial system.
There is also a risk that other countries will feel the impact.
The Bloody Bath of American Stocks
The U.S. House of Representatives on Monday rejected a plan to support the financial system, which was expected to cost up to $700 billion (nearly CZK 12 trillion).
Legislators ignored President George W. Bush’s call to support the plan.
According to Bush, the plan would address the underlying causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks suffered a bloodbath on Monday, and major stock indices saw the biggest decline in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index fell by nearly seven percent, with a similar decline last seen in 1987.
The index fell before the vote, but once it turned out that the bill had not passed in the House, the index found itself in a free fall.
Congress Resigns: U.S. Government May Pump $700 Billion into Banks
The top U.S. Congress and the government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of financial assistance agreement for the U.S. financial system.
The vote will be held early next week.
U.S. lawmakers have made a breakthrough in talks to approve a $700 billion bailout plan in the form of financial assistance to the U.S. financial system.
However, it has not yet been won.
Congressmen have to complete some details of the agreement before they can publish the final form of the law and vote on it.
The plan to support the financial system will be discussed on the floor of the House of Representatives on Monday.
Barney Frank, chairman of the House Banking and Financial Services Committee, told Reuters on Sunday.
According to sources, the plan could be voted on in the Senate on Wednesday.
According to economists, the announcement of the approval of the rescue plan should be the first significant psychological factor for the revival of financial markets.
Thereafter, however, there will be a sobriety due to the complexity of the mechanisms by which markets can be helped to achieve even in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made great progress.
We have resolved our differing views on what the market stabilization package should look like," Nancy Pelosi, a Democrat, told Bloomberg.
She said the final vote could take place on Sunday.
Lawmakers met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson on Sunday night to give the government fund a definitive shape.
It should buy back non-sellable mortgage assets from financial companies that drag financial companies into heavy losses and threaten the stability of the entire system.
"We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and must also be effective in the market.
We still need to continue with the recovery plan, but I think we’re there,” Paulson said.
Signal for Asian Trade
The global financial crisis is having a significant impact on the stock markets, which are declining sharply.
According to Nevada Democratic Senator Harry Reid, the legislators are trying to reach a final deal in Congress on Sunday.
They want to reassure investors before trading in Asian financial markets, which are the first in the time zone where a congressional decision could affect trading on Monday.
However, it is not yet clear with certainty when both chambers of the US Congress will vote on the law, nor whether they can fix the last-minute negotiations on a problem.
Legislators hope that it will be approved in the next few days.
However, the law is still subject to a number of changes.
The total amount earmarked for assistance to the system shall be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion should be made available as soon as possible, as President George Bush has demanded.
But Congress can block the release of the remaining amount if it feels the program is not fulfilling its function, followed by another $100 billion and then the final $350 billion.
Bush Appreciates Progress in Negotiations
The President may veto this decision, but Congress may override his veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program, which was to obtain funding to buy bad mortgage securities, the value of which has fallen because hundreds of thousands of Americans are unable to repay their mortgages, has remained.
"We worked out everything.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday and the Senate on Monday," Republican Senator Judd Gregg said.
President Bush is also pleased with the progress made in the negotiations.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said that Bush was pleased with Saturday’s progress and appreciated “both sides’ efforts to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy.”
Restriction of gold parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, the chief negotiator, said legislators had agreed on responsibilities for the money program, protecting taxpayers from losses, concluding reliefs, timing funding the plan.
The new law also aims to limit the so-called golden parachutes for directors of companies participating in the program and establishes a committee that will supervise the fund.
It should be run by the Ministry of Finance.
“We have worked very hard on this and we have made great progress towards an agreement that will work and be useful for the market and for all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also counts on help for homeowners who are having repayment problems.
The government should negotiate new installments on mortgages it buys in order to reduce the monthly cost of installments for debtors and allow them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological assistance
The proposed plan is a good idea, according to David Mark, chief economist at Patria Finance, but it will be very difficult to implement.
“And that’s because we don’t know what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets will be bought back.
This will be decisive for how the financial sector and the government will share the losses," Marek told iHNed.cz server this week.
Whether the plan will be approved now, or early next week, is not so significant, according to Mark.
"It is much more important that this week Congressmen agree that they support this plan and that they dedicate it as soon as possible.
The psychological significance of the agreement for approval to take place is the most important at the moment," Marek stressed.
Combat on knife blades: MP3 players against mobile phones.
We will advise you how to choose
While almost every mobile phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make a phone call.
It seems clear that it is better to buy only a phone.
Still, there are plenty of reasons for a person to get a separate player.
The choice depends entirely on the way of use and the claims of the future owner.
It’s probably hard to get a top-of-the-line expensive turntable at home to listen to the latest Maxim Turbulenc album.
On the one hand, such music products on LPs do not come from a qualitative point of view and there is no objective reason for this.
However, if you have vinyl with art rock, jazz or blues in your racks, you probably at least dream of such a turntable.
It is the same with music on the road, that is, music compressed, simplified - music in MP3.
There are also price and quality categories.
For some, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, just as a fan of Pink Floyd probably has a hard time tasting headphones for twenty crowns from the market.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is wide.
It also determines the battery life
Some top-notch music players can do much more than just play music, but what most mobiles don’t even happen to do.
No current device is as versatile as a phone.
In addition to the primary functions, telephoning and sesemescing, he can play music and video, both record, has a better, worse camera and maybe he can even navigate.
And if we take smartphones and communicators into account, you will have a small computer in your pocket.
It's a small miracle, because no refrigerator can grill, and no TV can photograph anything.
The versatility of the mobile also brings disadvantages.
The more features you use on your mobile, the sooner the indicator on the display will send you to the charger.
And playing music is one of the biggest hurdles of energy.
Few mobile phones can play music for more than ten to twelve hours, usually much less.
In this sense, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
In the case of cheap mobile phones, you should be aware that they will not play for more than a few hours.
If you still call here and there, get another charger to work for sure - this also applies to more expensive devices.
For MP3 players you will not have this problem, even the worst ones will last at least 9 hours of continuous operation on a single charge.
Another problem occurs when recording music to a mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, and moreover, not all of them can be directly connected to a computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly to a memory card, but only a few card readers can cope with the miniature memory cards used in mobile devices without reduction.
You do not need any special software for players except iPods.
Simply fill the device with music via USB from your computer.
Most mobile phones and players will create a music library themselves, sorted by the name of the performer, the name of the album, the genre or even the user's rating.
Some devices display only the tree structure of directories similar to Explorer in Windows, and some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with the operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobile phones are more capable
When choosing a specific device, you should be particularly interested in battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of audio output and, of course, control comfort.
If music is your backdrop and you listen to it every day for a short time, for example in a tram, you need any mobile phone that plays MP3.
That’s what almost any mobile phone can do.
You don’t even have to watch much of what music formats the phone or player can do.
MP3 will handle all and the vast majority of the music that gets to you will be in this format.
It is one of the most widely used and besides it, the vast majority of devices can also handle music in WMA format.
Less common is AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPods).
Better mobile phones also make it possible, for example, to buy music online.
All you have to do is visit the relevant website of the operator (or other provider) via mobile internet and buy a song or album.
This service in itself could already be a valid argument for the acquisition of a music mobile.
Unfortunately, the offer of operators is miserable and is usually limited to fast-drying radio hits.
Prices are also not the lowest.
However, it is generally assumed that this way of selling music (whether via GSM, internet or wireless internet) will be dominated by the music industry in the future.
Most people still carry their mobiles with them.
Whenever you get the urge to listen to something, you grab your phone in your pocket, while the MP3 player is forgotten at home.
However, it also depends on whether you always carry headphones or at least wired handsfree with you.
If not, you can use an integrated speaker that has almost every mobile, but only a minimum of MP3 players.
Probably the biggest advantage of music mobiles will be for many price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand.
For three and four thousand crowns you will get a very decent walkman.
However, most of the time you will be limited to the absence of an output on a regular headphone.
The best and technically the most equipped phones with a 3.5 mm port for regular headphones cost up to fifteen thousand.
The advantage of the players is, among other things, easy operation.
The simplest - not necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) - players can really control everyone.
The minimum of functions, the similarity of the control with a previously common cassette player or, for example, a turntable is obvious.
There is no risk of a collision in the form of an accidentally turned on mobile internet and subsequently a huge account for data transfer.
What device to touch
Even the cheapest phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have an interchangeable memory card slot (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of the relevant card you can fit in two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
For basic models, only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB are supported.
Only the most expensive ones can cope with 8 GB of memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, reach out to Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or Iriver.
Depending on the capacity (maximum 2 GB), you do not have to spend more than CZK 1,100.
If you’re a more demanding listener, go for specialized mobiles – walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokias and Samsungs).
These devices have separate control buttons for MP3 and thus the comfort of the operator is closer to a separate MP3 player.
Next up is Sony Ericsson, whose mobile phones from the walkman series have the same user interface as the separately sold MP3 players.
The same service and in the same price range up to 4,000 CZK, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours), MP3 players will take you away from the above brands.
The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Possibly
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite advanced and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Yet we are missing something here - a virtual operator that would force the classics to discount.
Maybe he won't be long.
We have written many times on Mobil.cz about the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
Moreover, the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> also confirmed this, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher in our country than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges, this may lead to a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic stay so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really wants to get into the fight.
Maybe it sounds paradoxical, because we have three mobile networks and penetration is over 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to bet that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xA1>k, Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), who has repeatedly said that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that the classical operator with its own network no longer seems to have too many chances (by the way, it would probably be difficult to search for frequencies).
But there is one more option - a virtual operator.
It was the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that brought a significant reduction in prices, to which then the classical operators had to react.
Even before the introduction of sticks such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, similar voices sounded in the UK as in our country.
But it turned out that the place for such operators is and can be really successful.
We don’t have to go too far for examples.
In February of this year we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, this operator managed to gain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator there.
Behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns, among other things, U:fone in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to operate effectively, they need far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They do not carry with them relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators are usually profiled as low-cost - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often balanced by a narrower range of services.
Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be quite a good move to bet on an unscrambled target group.
This operator is specifically aimed at men.
“Administrative guys choose Mobilking – an operator they like and can trust,” says David Seibertz, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, running this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could be grasped in our country.
Vodafone press spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for the segmental approach on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated in terms of service offerings."
In the Czech Republic without a chance, say mobile operators
But it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not seem too hopeful.
Rather, Mobilking will be launched in other countries of our region," Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1>, a spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, said in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, it confirmed that existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything in their power to ensure that no potential competitors arise.
GTS Novera Group has not been interested in launching a virtual mobile operator for a long time, which would like to take the next step to become a real competitor of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We are very interested in offering our customers not only fixed, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already made progress in negotiations with some of them," said Pavel Kaidl, a spokesman for the group.
Maybe he's looking for better times.
From unofficial information, it seems that the first virtual operator should be expected perhaps by the end of the year.
For now, however, its creation is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
“At the moment, we do not believe that there is room on the Czech market for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far, no entity has addressed us with a comprehensive and serious project in this area," Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> from the Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 press department told Mobil.cz.
Other operators are also referring to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> adds, in rare agreement with the O2 statement: “We have not yet seen any viable and mutually beneficial business project on which to build on.”
He added: “T-Mobil’s network is unlikely to have a virtual operator by the end of the year.
At this point, we would already have to have a specific agreement on the table in order to be able to consider it in this short term."
Vodafone is paying more attention to meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> says: "We are open to dealing with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we consider to be the most profitable from the point of view of our customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities - with operators one hand
The procedure of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean increased competition, would lead to a decrease in prices and thus to a decrease in their profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor to enter?
The fact that when the operators are concerned about something, they can pull a single rope, is also evidenced by the pulling around the creation of the U:fon.
Probably the biggest pressure towards <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> went at the time of the creation of the U:fon from the company T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> website.
But now U:fon is suitable as an argument for not allowing a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> said: “The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently been further strengthened by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another player would place high demands on him and especially on his services."
Due to this approach of mobile operators, however, there is a complete lack of interest of the Czech regulatory authorities.
This is not just a position of the Czech Republic, which unfortunately, unlike the UK and other developed countries, has no power to interfere in competition.
These belong exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
But he took his typical stance on the whole issue.
“The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after a contract has been concluded between the mobile operator and the virtual operator for the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, because the offer of potential interested parties was probably not interesting enough for classical operators," said Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa from the Department of External Relations of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
The statements made in this way by the representatives of the operators are probably not surprising.
It is more than a matter of concern to an authority that is supposed to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses its position on the market.
Especially, when Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa adds: "Abroad, where virtual operators are commonly operating, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile phone services."
Obviously, however, the pressure on the correct functioning of the market environment and the fall in prices is not in the interests of the EAGGF.
In truth, shocking to the whole case is the touching coherence of the three mobile operators that results from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence is offered entirely by itself.
Like the exact same price of gasoline at the gas stations, it’s certainly just a matter of chance and tough competition.
"The Authority has not found any evidence of anti-competitive conduct in this case, and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore does not have adequate increased responsibility for their behaviour on the market.
The necessary tools for opening up the mobile market for virtual operators are probably also available to the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa said in a statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications are the single market from a competitive point of view.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - the creation of a virtual operator always requires the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator - quite logically - has a monopoly on its network.
So in a certain segment it must necessarily be dominant.
However, even if we do not admit this argument, it should be at least a warning for the EEAS that three mobile operators are proceeding noticeably similarly.
At the same time, the complaints of a number of interested parties (including GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles when negotiating with all operators.
Responsibilities at the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications, with which <0xC3><0x9A>OHS hands away from the whole matter.
We have met with him in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, until the recently adopted amendments to the Telecommunications Act with the extension of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>’s powers to the field of competition in telecommunications, many experts have promised to improve the situation.
This needs to be known more than well by the representatives of the EPA, but apparently their interests are elsewhere.
That's what happens when no one's watching
However, the functioning of some pseudo-virtual operators, which exist in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that issue their own mobile phone price lists, but they are only partially public.
It is usually a multi-level marketing company.
Our own mobile phone services include Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many more.
The prices of these companies usually only reach the chosen ones.
The magic lies in the fact that the company acts towards the operator as a classic corporate customer who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As a significant customer, you will then receive special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If there are any cases you are talking about, they could be a breach of the terms of the contract that we are dealing with and could result in the termination of cooperation with the company," Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> answered our question on this issue.
It is, however, unlikely that such an activity would not have occurred to responsible people from mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, it can be thousands of customers.
None of the operators are opposed to such a procedure.
These companies have significant profits from their activities and, unlike real virtual operators, they do not in any way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> points out possible problems: "The law of similar speculation allows, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card in their phone is not kept in their name, so they cannot make full use of it as regular customers of mobile operators.
But that’s what should be weird at least.
In addition, another question opens for the EPA.
If mobile operators close their eyes to a similar procedure, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It must be added that the EAGGF has a fairly strong authority to detect such an activity and, if it does not want to, is not satisfied with the explanation of the operators that they have no idea of anything and their commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we won't be the most expensive
As has already been stated several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a noticeable decline in prices for services.
In virtually all the countries where virtual operators were created, the classical operators tried to more or less defend their creation.
The arguments used by Jimi were virtually identical - too small, possibly too saturated market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In developed countries, however, it was at this time that regulators intervened, defending not the interests of mobile operators, but their customers.
Whether through formal measures or informal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created and another was packed on it.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators turn the whole case around like a hot potato.
From our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that the ambiguity in competences is more than suitable for them in these cases.
But let's not throw the flint into the grain.
If the behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator really soon appears, the Czech mobile market may be moving again.
If one of the operators has admitted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS to remain incapable of rejecting (discrimination) other interested parties.
And maybe we'll stop calling the shots than the rest of Europe.
