Even rats have feelings.
When rats or cockroaches run away from danger, does this mean that they also feel fear?
The neurologist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals have feelings.
But how could it be verified that they feel the same way when they behave the same way as we do?
For several years, contributions from well-known scientists have been published in the online magazine "Edge".
SPIEGEL ONLINE in its series presents selected answers to the question "What do you consider to be true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove it so far, when we cannot prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case we can at least hope, because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, once we start to engage with a different species and open up questions of perception or general consciousness, we enter the inaccessible terrain because the hardware does not match.
When the rat gets into danger, it will do the same as many other animals: it will pretend to be dead, fleeing, or attacking.
Humans behave in a similar way, which some scientists deduce to comparable subjective experience.
I don't believe that, though.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to the experience of animals.
This is because circuits associated with human consciousness almost always include the lateral prefrontal cortex (because of its share of short-term memory and executive or managerial functions).
This vast area is significantly more developed in humans than in other primates, and seems to be missing in other creatures.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, among them knowledge of who we are, and the ability to plan and make decisions, there is reason to believe that man differs even from other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity could be the language essence of a person: because so much of his perception is associated with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, we could exclude animals.
But even if language consciousness did not matter, it would certainly be influenced by language, so that animal consciousness, whatever it may be, would probably differ from most states of our consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness looks like in other animals.
When, as something internal and subjective, it is not possible to measure or, due to special hardware, to analyze it on the basis of our own experience, its exploration puts us before great problems.
Most of my outputs relate to the content of conscious experience, but besides that, there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more accessible scientifically.
It would be possible to examine the processes in the consciousness of animals regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in studies of short-term memory in primates, especially on the example of visualization.
But this approach, which was pursued by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, focuses on neural correlates of consciousness rather than causal mechanisms: both may be identical, but they may not be.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the nonfrontal cortex for the realization of visualization.
What does that mean for feelings?
I derive them from the fact that the emotional system, such as the fear system, is activated in the brain conscious of its own activities.
What we call “fear” is the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) makes use of operational memory.
Seen from this angle, feelings are closely related to those areas of the cortex that are characterized by primates, and especially people.
In connection with the linguistic nature, there is a subtle gradation of perception, because with the help of words and grammar we can distinguish and categorize states so that we can attribute them to others alongside ourselves.
Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that feelings arise from more primitive activities in the areas of the cortex and brain stem devoted to physical sensations, similar to Jaak Pankseep, who, however, focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it could easily participate in the sensations perceived by multiple animal races.
In theory, I can’t argue with that, but I think it’s unproven.
Pankseep argues that what appears to us as fear in rats and humans probably feels the same to both organisms: But how is it possible to verify, Pankseep says, whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave similarly?
The cockroach flees from danger - does he also feel fear?
In my view, the mere similarity of behavior cannot prove the conformity of experience.
It is true that the neural comparison moves us further: rats and humans have similar brain strains, not even the brain of a cockroach.
But is the brain stem responsible for feelings?
And even if it were possible to prove it in humans: how would we want to prove it in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?), have feelings.
But I really don't know how to prove it.
And because their feelings are probably fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness rests on special circuits and language), I’d rather study emotional behavior than emotional perception of rats.
In any case, in this case, we can expect progress at the neural level if we measure the same in rats and in humans.
As with rats, I don’t examine language and consciousness, I don’t even examine feelings, because I don’t know if they exist.
It can be considered short-sighted, but I prefer to move forward rather than repeatedly throw myself against the wall.
I'm a practical emotionalist.
