The debate on bilingualism: immersion in English
In this edition of Focused on Education, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi will discuss the position of candidates for bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, an academic in California and director of education at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is a co-author of “Worse Than You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs to Choose Schools.”
Effectively addressing Hispanic voters is a daunting matter.
Barack Obama’s educational agenda only proves it.
Obama’s campaign notes that “African-American and Hispanic students are significantly less likely to study than white students,” which is true.
To combat such performance disparities, Obama’s education agenda especially promotes, among other things, “transient bilingual education” for those who are just learning English.
The question for Barack Obama, however, remains whether his commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes the use of languages other than English in the classroom, is no stronger than his interest in reducing performance disparities.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, a charter primary school in Los Angeles East.
Students of this school are in the vast majority of cases Hispanic from low-income families.
More than a third of students, many of whom have only recently arrived, are still learning English.
Yet in the 2008 state tests of mathematics, an incredible one hundred percent of fourth-grade pupils got to the highest level.
Nearly as astoundingly, ninety-three percent of fourth-grade pupils reached the highest level in state tests of English language and literature.
This incredible success was achieved by a different method than Obama prefers.
Sixth Street emphasizes control and practice, constant assessment of abilities, and access without excuses.
Further, and Obama should notice, according to Linda Mikels, director of Sixth Street, the school’s pedagogical approach to those who are just learning English is “complete immersion.”
Immersion in English emphasizes the almost privileged use of English in teaching.
Ms. Mikels, who is opposed to bilingual education, told me, "We had a tremendous success with one brand new student from Mexico - after twelve months you would enter the class and not know what it was."
"It works," she said, "it works for us."
Would Obama take a school as a Sixth Street Prep as a model, what should other schools with large proportions of Hispanic and English-taught pupils look like?
The results that the school achieves should make the answer to this question self-evident, but the educational agenda of its own party (the National Education Association is a long-standing advocate of bilingual education) and its own consistent support for bilingual education.
While Obama agrees that immigrants should learn English, he recently trivialized the matter when he said people should stop worrying about “only English” laws.
Instead, “you should make sure your children speak Spanish,” he said.
If Obama really wants to erase the performance gaps, he should rather think carefully about the educational patterns that work, rather than ridicule them and trivialize them.
Oil declines sharply due to renewed economic fears
Oil prices fell sharply on Monday due to fears that even the U.S. plan to save the financial markets would not have to revive the economy.
Futures oil prices fell 7 percent to $99.80 per barrel in the morning trading on the New York Commodity Exchange.
Since last Monday, prices have fallen by more than twenty dollars per barrel.
In the past two weeks, commodity markets have been rocked by financial turmoil on Wall Street and also by a pair of powerful hurricanes in the Gulf of Mexico.
After reaching a peak of $145.29 per barrel in July, prices fell to almost $90 per barrel earlier this month, rebounding in a wave of huge financial market uncertainty.
Anxiety gripped investors again on Monday, even after the U.S. Congressional Presidium announced it had reached an agreement this weekend on the largest rescue plan in history.
This report was overshadowed by fresh concerns that the financial crisis is far from over.
In the latest episode of the ongoing meltdown, the government announced that the Citigroup Group will acquire a banking division of Wachovia Corporation.
Meanwhile, the Belgian, Dutch and Luxembourg governments partly nationalized the European financial conglomerate Fortis.
Analysts at Barclays Capital said the furious weekend talks that led to the plan to save the economy "prove to be incapable of reviving the market mood."
As the economic situation worsens, demand for commodities, including oil, is expected to decline.
“Prospects for global equity, interest rates and foreign exchange markets have been severely shattered,” Deutsche Bank analysts wrote in a report to investors.
“We believe that commodities will not be able to escape the disease.
From a commodity perspective, our biggest concern is the extent to which the American virus is spreading around the world, and especially to China.”
Analysts at this bank have cut their expectations for next year as oil consumption has fallen due to slower economic growth, and have cut their gasoline price forecasts for 2009 by about 20 percent.
