The Pride and Obstacles of Black Lives in a Separate City
Hidden among the scenic amusement parks of greater Orlando, a few miles from everything shiny, noisy, and huge, lies a quiet city in which the pride and demandingness of African-American life comes to life.
Eatonville, the first completely black city to be incorporated into the state and where Zora Neale Hurston spent her childhood, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "a city of five lakes, three croquet courts, three hundred squats, three hundred squats, three hundred good swimmers."
Now it's a pilgrimage place.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Zora! Eatonville Festival to pay tribute to Hurston, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
The city she described remains a no-go, though she made it a stop for tourists by including it in a Florida tour guide created by the Federal Writers project from the time of the economic crisis.
It is still as independent, dignified and private as it was in the 1930s when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted and did not share their real feelings with a white man who “knows so little about us that he doesn’t even know what he’s missing.”
Even today, in the year that the Black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, calls for an open debate about races, many locals remain wary of the views of strangers.
“We’re paying close attention to how our story is told,” says 59-year-old Hortense Jones, who has lived here since birth and is a member of the city’s oldest parish.
"It must be right."
Eatonville has long been characterized as a paradox of triumph and effort.
It is both a historical model of the Black rise and a community of almost 2,400 people, where the poverty rate is double the national average.
It is a center of literature, but also of oaks, a shadowy example of the southern rural Black culture - sometimes despised, sometimes praised - that arose from American slavery.
Not surprisingly, the locals are both proud and protective.
And concerns about Eatonville really started with Zora, which is the only way the Hurstons are called here.
She introduced her hometown to the world through heartfelt books full of idioms such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
The five paragraphs of the Florida Tourist Guide turned the city a short distance into Highway 17, which leads through the often-passed center of Florida, into a stage of black history and human drama.
With the blast of a big drum in life and literature, Hurston introduced readers to the shop of First Eatonville Mayor Joe Clark, and then turned to more personal places.
"To the left of the roadside," she wrote, "is a white, brown-decorated, modern national school with well-maintained courtyards and playgrounds, which Howard Miller always takes care of, even though he can't read or write much."
She also mentioned the new husband of the widow of Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and anything that fits in an hourly hotel."
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston linked Eatonville to self-government, but also to illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
This was clearly not a typical Fodor's publishing house.
In fact, it was not a portrait that everyone would appreciate.
“She said it the way it was,” says 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson’s girls who made Hurston immortal by quoting men who sang dirty songs about their beauty.
"Some people didn't like it," she added.
Hurston is still remembered as a chipping eccentric who often returned after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Seventy-seven-year-old Augustus Franklin remembers that most of the time, when she came to the city, she arrived without notice in a huge Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants in the city, which is still proud of its dignified dress.
Most of the people were fascinated, Franklin said, but many scoffed.
"The people of Zora have always loved to see," Franklin said.
But, he added, hovering on a chair on the back terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "she never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were removed from the press.
It seemed that Eatonville, along with the rest of the world, had forgotten about it.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had previously lived.
There were no major mourning ceremonies or major public readings in Eatonville.
“I don’t think they understood her importance to the world or her legacy at all,” said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston’s 2003 biography Wrapped in Rainbows.
Change came in the 80s of the 20th century.
Representatives of Orange County wanted to extend the city's five-lane highway instead of Kennedy Boulevard, which is the local two-lane main road.
Orlando's cruising has already pushed Interstate 4 through the city's western outskirts.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was still coming from a difficult historical period.
Forced integration, along with other things, ended the relatively idyllic isolation of this community.
In the fifties of the 20th century, the struggle to mix races brought hatred to the threshold of the community.
“At the time, a bunch of white guys, they came and threw oranges and stuff at the people who sat on the side,” Franklin said.
"We actually had a lady who killed it.
They got out of the melon car."
In a letter to The Orlando Sentinel in 1955, Hurston challenged the Supreme Court's demand for forced integration and declared his decision in the Brown v. Chamber of Education case to be "offensive to my race rather than celebratory."
Residents now claim that the desegregation of schools, although positive in some areas, reduced cohesion in Eatonville and undermined the courage of the local youth.
"Black children were used to hugging - I remember that - you hugged your teacher in the morning, you hugged your teacher in the evening," said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Elly Dinkins and executive director of the Preserve the Eatonville Community.
This lasted until the teachers and students came from the same place, she added.
"You're not hugging your white teacher because your white teacher - I mean there's a cultural barrier," said Miss Nathiri.
Civil rights, however, have helped to create space for many more of Zora Neale Hurston - black writers, actors and artists like her who have risen above prejudices with light-hearted self-esteem and quotes such as "How can anyone deny the delight of my presence!
I don't understand that."
In 1975, Alice Walker traveled to Hurston's unmarked grave and began fighting to revive her reputation.
Five years later, Hurston's highly acclaimed biography by Robert E. Hemenway re-entered the American canon.
The highway project arrived just as Eatonville’s most famous daughter found the lights of the ramp again.
Her former neighbors, the Hurstons, now considered her a savior.
To show what can happen to their highway to destroy, the community began planning the Hurston Festival in 1988.
Thousands of fans arrived at the inaugural event two years later, and many return to the celebration every January.
After a few years, the state withdrew from the highway project.
"The five currents of the highway have resurrected, you would say, a real civil pride," Nathiri said.
Boyd said it simpler: "Tomorrow saved Eatonville."
The victory over the highway project helped to change the image of the city.
Outsiders like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who started going to the local church in 1993, began to appear in greater numbers, and residents began to reevaluate the past.
Eatonville joined the National Historical Register in 1998.
The new one-story library (named, of course, after Hurston) was opened in 2006 on the re-asphalted and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando can sometimes act as a cobbled alley in the summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded with only 27 black families in the 1980s.
(Today it is 90% black.)
Strangers who come looking for the story and meaning of Eatonville are still often treated with caution.
Permission for most interviews is required in advance, and certain things — like wall paintings in the oldest Eatonville church painted by whites and depicting blacks in the fields — are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Jones, a bold, self-confident teacher who loves the rich red, still fear that their isolated community will not be properly understood.
And even as the Hurston Festival grew, so did the domestic pride.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw her entire race: beautiful, with problems and so on, not better, not worse, and equally proud, creative, hard-working, foolish and diverse as other American races and ethnicities.
The voice of Franklin’s nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, echoes his sincere love for the community as he plans to return to Eatonville after college to work for the local government or police, which he says would use some help.
And even younger ones, like the 11-year-old twins from Winter Park Alondra and Alexie Kenon, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people, when they just pass through here, think, 'Hm, this city is nothing against the others,'" Alondra Kenon told the church on Sunday.
"But if you really stop and take a look at history, it's a very nice city."
Here in New York, we all speak financially fluently.
At first glance, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan were to stay away from the newsstands and the huge television screens on Times Square, they wouldn’t realize they were standing in the middle of a storm.
They would never have guessed that in the glazed bee hive of offices above their heads, every day the bankers and investment fund managers who monopolize New York have the worst “bad day in the office” since the 1929 crisis.
The messengers are still whistling metal trolleys on the sidewalks and transfer muffin bakers to breakfast meetings.
The Hispanics still move between the turrets and wear, like human mules, fifty iron-clad shirts that hang from the scales on their backs.
The office rats are still waiting in line for their morning bagel at the street food stalls, and it is still impossible to get a yellow taxi on a weekday between 4 and 7 p.m.
It didn’t seem like a crisis at all until, with all the talk of pessimism, I decided to set up a savings account on Thursday afternoon.
Even though I had timed this task to cover up with a late afternoon siesta at my local JP Morgan Chase branch, there were already about twenty people waiting in line.
Not in front of checkouts to pick up or store cash, but in front of a counter where older customers order checkbooks, tourists ask for a way to shop for Macy’s mixed goods, and new customers set up accounts.
Most of the people in front of me, as I learned from Starr, my “licensed personal banker,” came for the same reason as I did.
But compared to me, they have already taken their savings from smaller banks in places where they came from, such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania or Staten Island.
They picked up money from so-called thrifts (a bit like construction savings banks), money unions, and from the types of savings banks whose branches operate in only one state, and who claim to care for their customers as if they were a family.
In the past year, 15 such banks have been quietly bankrupt.
A few days ago, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in assets, went bankrupt, and when New Yorkers returned home for the weekend on Friday night, another bank, Wachovia, with $440 billion in assets, tried to catch a rescue buyer.
The staff of the offices and shops that stood in front of me and were afraid of another collapse, moved their cash to a bank that is perceived as a safe haven and that does most of the rescue on Wall Street.
Ordinary New Yorkers have learned financially in the last week.
A woman in my local Chinese supermarket spoke on the phone and spoke to Lehman Borthers, that bank that went bankrupt, and to her exterminated executive, Dick Fuld, with such familiarity, as if she were teasing a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the uniformed 50-year-old housewife of my co-worker, changed the subject of our ordinary conversation—Brad, Angelina, or my food deliveries.
After my visit to the bank, she told me: "I now have my savings in money market funds.
I moved it, I'm not going to risk it."
