"To capture the real character, I photograph the master off-stage." Günther Bauer - photographer
No heels, no phone calls, no costumes.
Only the essence of the great flamenco masters, detached from the focus on interpretation - this is the only way to achieve a relaxed expression of a man or a woman.
On the one hand, an artist.
On the other hand, a man.
Inseparable, aside from privacy, in those moments away from the audience - then you can see a confidential gesture, the depth of a lethally captured look or the passionate gesticulation of hands that are carefree, because they are not going to get on the scene.
The German Günther Bauer alternates in "Flamenco-people" the theatrical performances with singers, dancers and guitarists with the lesser-known face of the masters.
With this intention, the photographer composes a unique iconography of flamenco from different environments.
The exhibition, which takes place as part of the Mes de la Fotograf<0xC3><0xAD>a Flamenca program, "reflects the ever-growing international significance of flamenco," says the author, explaining that "Flamenco-people" "can be any kind of people, but if you look at the photographs, you'll find that um is not a typical image.
These people portrayed "on the street" are artists capable of conveying passion, sadness, joy... and completely captivating the audience.
To capture the personality of these artists, it is not necessary to take photos on stage.
It has its own personality and character inside.
I was interested in creating a relaxed atmosphere that would allow me to capture the personality of flamenco giants.
Enchanted by the festival "Cante de las Minas", Bauer began in 1997 a long journey of portraying flamenco singers, guitarists and dancers on a record camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and material, resemble classical photography.
The use of different stylistic means is contrary to the classical basis of the image and lends it a contemporary spirit, which is an idea that, according to Bauer himself, flamenco mirrors: "Music with very traditional roots, but it does not cease to surprise and develop."
What draws the audience is not the action of the dance, the song or the game itself, but the personality and character of the artist.
The search for the moment when we meet the most essential, the spirit that manifests itself in the way of perception, being and experiencing, that was and is a constant of work presented during these days in the gallery of El Fotomata.
This selection of almost seventy photographed artists form famous flamenco characters such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales and Vicente Amigo.
The project has become an anthology of flamenco and will soon be published in a book containing portraits.
The passion for portraiture brought Bauer to the idea of repeating the idea on the "Portraits of Sports Veterans" ("SportARTproject") two years ago.
Although their concept is different from "Flamenco-people", the photographer admits that "picturing people, getting to know them and having the opportunity for a moment, whether longer or shorter, to enter their lives - that's my passion.
