Drivers repeatedly caught with alcohol in their blood will have to install "alcolock"
The Interior Ministry requires that a driver with three administrative penalties for driving under the influence of alcohol must install in his car a system that will prevent him from starting the car intoxicated or if he does not breathe.
The proposal was announced in June of this year and is now included in the annual report of the Supreme Public Prosecutor’s Office, according to which it is a pilot project that will last one year.
Its goal is to return the driver behind the wheel, which is why drivers will also have to undergo a traffic retraining course.
In addition to the National Office for Transport Safety, the Directorate-General for Transport (DGT) and the Foundation of the Institute of Technology for Automotive Safety (FITSA) will participate in this experience.
According to statistics, between 30 and 75% of motorists accused more than once of driving intoxicated will again sit behind the wheel.
Alcolock should prevent this, as it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the level of alcohol in the exhaled air and prevents the car from starting if the driver does not breathe before or if it is recorded higher than the permissible concentration of alcohol.
Its price exceeds 1,000 euros and would have to be paid by the culprit himself.
A study carried out in this regard in the USA in 2007 showed that infractions were reduced by 65 % in the first year since the introduction of the device.
In Spain, it is estimated that 115 lives could be saved each year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to deal with this behavior before it results in a criminal offence.
And in order to help its introduction, since the legal regulation can be carried out in the usual way, the necessary adjustment of criminal provisions requires a change in the law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any sales version, although it has already been installed in some industrial and public service vehicles.
Tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on the proposal of the PSOE (Spanish Workers’ Socialist Party), which recommends the installation of this system in school buses, as is the case in France.
