Talking from sleep
Some children talk at night.
I don't mean those who wake up and tell us something that happened the day before, but the children who talk while they sleep.
When it happens for the first time, it may frighten you, but in reality it is irrelevant.
This is a harmless sleep disorder called somnilokvie.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure many of you have been told that he spoke from his sleep at night.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (for example, once in a lifetime with high fevers), or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once in a few months...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There is only one reason that explains its origin.
It is often associated with other sleep disorders, such as nightmares, night rages, nocturnal enuresis (nighttime assistance) or lunacy, but it may not be so.
As mentioned earlier, it can often be accompanied by very high fevers, stressful or irritable situations.
In any case, this is a little researched phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also different.
The child can speak in a calm voice, say individual words, whisper, or just the opposite (crying, crying, long speeches...).
In cases where it manifests itself with great force, it would be appropriate for the child to observe and consult with a specialist to find out if he has a problem that causes him great anxiety and manifests itself in this way.
We have said that this is a harmless disorder, so it is not treated only if it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with apnea syndrome or permanent stress).
However, we can do this by keeping in mind a few very simple preventive measures, such as:
Try not to disturb the child too much before he goes to sleep.
So look for quiet games and avoid scary or somewhat violent TV shows or series.
For very nervous children and those who can relax, it is possible to use relaxation techniques that will help them gain some inner peace.
This will allow the child to sleep more peacefully.
When somnilokvie appears, try to stay calm.
Remember that it is harmless to the child and that he will remember nothing of what happened the next day.
Helpful advices
Don't be him.
It's useless because he's not conscious and you're interrupting his sleep.
Even if he speaks, he sleeps, and therefore he rests.
Remember that if you feel that you are very worried several times in a row, it would be advisable to seek advice or find out what causes such anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he is saying (which is not so common), avoid the temptation to question him and draw information from him.
It will be useless because when she sleeps, she is not aware that she can organize her thoughts.
Moreover, you will hear what he is saying, but you do not know what he is saying, and therefore why he is saying it, so pay close attention to how you interpret the information and to what conclusions you come to.
Never tell a child that you can ask him about his secrets at night.
It's not funny.
