Conversation - Blood, which is certain again
Héma-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of its founding yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was rightly delighted that Héma-Québec had become one of the most reliable and effective blood suppliers in the world.
Above all, he regained public confidence, which was seriously shaken after the blood-contaminated scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is generally known, the state blood supply managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Board was contaminated with the Immune Deficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the light of this drama and public outcry, the Canadian government launched a public inquiry in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, aimed at explaining the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and formulating recommendations not to repeat such a disaster.
While Judge Krever lingered on the report, some provinces set in motion a committee aimed at planning a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this role was taken up by the Gélinea Committee.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were established in Canada: Héma-Québec, which was to administer Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Society for the Supply of All Provinces and Both Territories.
“When Héma-Québec started its activities in 1998, barely 38% of people still had confidence in the Quebec blood system,” recalls Dr. Décary.
"The situation was depressing.
Through continuous efforts to increase the safety of blood products and continuous work in this area, we have regained public confidence over the following years," he says, proudly adding that by the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of the Quebec population had already trusted Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary does not lose sight of the fact that "confidence is something very fragile".
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
“At the time, we were witnessing in Europe many cases of human-like mad cow disease, a new variant of the disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease,” says the woman who has led the company since its inception in 1998.
"And we had no idea if this disease could spread with blood.
We have therefore relied on one of the basic recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which, in the event that we do not know this and when the spread of a serious disease is at stake, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by degeneration of the brain, inevitably leading to death.
Thus, in April 1999, we rejected blood from people who had stayed in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
A few years ago, it was safely proven that this disease is transmitted by blood.
So this episode showed us that sticking to the precautionary principle made sense.”
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: tests using nucleic acid (NAT), which allow to detect in the donor blood directly the presence of the virus itself, and not the presence of antibodies on which the tests were based.
NAT tests have shortened the deafening period that occurs between the moment of infection of the patient and the moment when our techniques can detect the first viruses in the blood, explains the specialist.
We were able to shorten this period to less than a week.
We have substantially reduced the risk that some donors could be infected without knowing it and without being able to find out.
These improvements have made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of getting AIDS through blood transfusions.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of getting HIV-contaminated blood.
“In other words, it means that before someone gets infected with HIV, 12 million blood products will have to be distributed.
Since Héma-Québec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products annually, it will take 24 years before the first case of HIV transmission through a blood product appears.
I believe that today we can receive or prescribe the blood transfusions needed to heal," said Hém-Québec's chief executive.
“The challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know what pathogenic element may appear in the system.
Just last year, a chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted to the blood by stinging insects.
We need to be constantly cautious," continues Dr. Décary, stressing that Héma-Québec must also expect sufficient supplies in addition to safe supply.
“Needs are growing because the population is getting older.
As a result of more aggressive cancer treatment, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging population also has consequences for the blood donor network, which on average consists of only 3% of Quebecers eligible to donate.
Each healthy person is at least 18 years old, corresponding to the criteria of admissibility, but can only donate blood once every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer blood are not accepted because, for example, they are carriers of AIDS or malaria, and if they have visited a country where mudslides are common, they are excluded for one year.
“With these 3%, we can maintain a condition that meets the needs of hospitals.
Deficiencies are very rare.
However, the members of the donor network should be supplemented in proportion to how they age and can no longer donate blood.
However, it is difficult to convince people to give blood, especially to keep them and encourage them to become regular donors.
“Life today is so untied that we rarely find an hour to donate blood,” said Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissue, such as bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin, which is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analysed, processed, and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, which was previously considered biomedical waste, is filled with blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our 1,000 umbilical cord blood into the bank, and we expect to collect more than 1,000 of them a year.
At the beginning of next year, we should start offering them for transplants," says Dr. Décary, who describes the umbilical cord blood collection program as very popular.
"Some mothers are disappointed that they do not have access to it," because Héma-Québec does not have enough funds to offer this comprehensive and expensive program to all hospitals in Quebec.
