Opinions - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Discourse
In a September 17 issue, Le Devoir printed a letter from Patrick J. Garver, executive vice president of Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
With Orwellian logic, it confirms that the world’s largest gold producer has launched a lawsuit against three authors and a poor little publisher for insulting honor in order to spark “transparent public debate” and demands six million of them.
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge the truth, especially in the case of prosecution for insult to honor, but the law.
It’s no surprise that Garver completely misses this crucial distinction.
Or is it the best way for Barrick Gold to lead a public debate, to bring to ruin anyone who would dare to defend the opposite position?
Whatever the case, the authors and publisher of Noir Canada (Black Canada) will be forced to spend lavish sums to be prepared to defend themselves and fight in a highly unbalanced battle against an army of lawyers backed by the almost bottomless pockets of a mining company.
The tactic in these unbalanced struggles, moreover, often consists in ruining the defendants in order to enforce a conciliation procedure that will shut the mouth of the other party and also frighten anyone who dares to dedicate himself to this matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it should have presented its view of the whole thing to public opinion.
Contrary to what is happening in several countries where Barrick Gold is active, in Canada, the debate under normal circumstances is about exchanging ideas, and not about the wounds with the earrings.
So it was not enough for the mining companies to open up their books, their documentation and set up a real debate through newspapers, media, publications and the funding of independent scientific teams that could bring light to the whole thing.
Barrick Gold, however, seems to have no confidence in public opinion and scathingly rejects petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can demand a “public debate” while at the same time disparaging the opinions of the same public?
It seems that this word in the vice-presidential world refers only to the fat-paid lawyers, and not to all Canadians; that is a rather narrow concept of the term.
In a democracy, they also have the right to speak out.
Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - that the public, which supports Noir Canada authors and publishers, does so primarily because it rejects the brutal ways of mining companies.
The public is ready to hear Barrick and judge the matter, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, not within what many perceive as a prosecution, in which the defendant is to be silenced (as part of its prosecution "public debate" the company Barrick by the way has just reported about, the official statement of Canada Novuvivi<0xC4><0x87>).
If we ignore Garver’s surreal speech, the prosecution initiated by Barrick Gold is a direct attack on the university’s freedom to investigate and seek the truth that is essential to every democratic society.
Overall, it denies the right to cite credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which constitute the very basis of intellectual activity.
If, in a country like Canada, it is impossible to study and discuss topics that are disliked by the rich companies of this world without being subjected to repeated persecution, who else will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could be created if it followed the scientific standards used by Noir Canada.
He has a right to an answer.
The university environment to which we belong has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s exaggerated lawsuit clearly shows that despite what he claims, he has no slightest desire to lead a transparent debate.
For the university world, this is a loss, as well as for public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place measures that would limit this type of unwarranted prosecution.
Operations to Save Wall Street – Democrats and Republicans Understand
The Bush administration and Congressional backers, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the biggest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
A new version of the $700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has been lurking on Wall Street for months has yet to be approved by both chambers of Congress.
In particular, it envisages: better control of elected representatives over its application, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of saved public money, new measures to capture the amount of houses seized due to non-payment, and the right to monitor the amount of wages paid to managers of saved companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, Speaker of the House of Representatives Nancy Pelosi, and Representative of the Republicans at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced this good news yesterday, minutes after midnight, following the end of a two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great progress and reached an agreement that will be effective in the markets," Bush administration spokesman Henry Paulson said in a statement.
“Everything was done so that the real economy and ordinary Americans were safe from the crisis just going on on Wall Street,” he said.
"This is a crucial point: if we don't do it, the trauma, chaos and disruption of Americans' daily lives will be huge," Gregg said.
Over the past few hours, the negotiations have been on maximum turns for fear of the effect that the next failure would have on the mood of investors.
The time limit set was the opening of the markets this morning.
Both candidates for the U.S. president were invited to the negotiations later, and both spoke out rather for the agreement, without neglecting to express their dissatisfaction with the need to resort to such an extreme solution.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has signed a supplement to the agreement on some measures, notably the one aimed at allowing homeowners to retain their homes, and the wages of state-run workers saved by companies.
“When we ask taxpayers to take special measures for the irresponsibility of some people, there is nothing to congratulate.
However, these measures are necessary," he explained on the waves of television.
His Republican rival John McCain, who was asked by another station if he would vote for the proposed plan, replied, "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
“The rough features that I’ve read [show] that it’s something we’re all going to have to spend and use to move forward.
“Choosing inaction is simply unacceptable,” he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to buy out dubious debts and risky and non-sales assets of U.S. financial institutions with taxpayers’ money.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis triggered by a bubble burst in the real estate market, which first led to the collapse of risky mortgage loans (subprimes), then transferred to other, more widespread forms of loans (PCAA) and resulted in the freezing of cash and the collapse of banks and finances.
The fall of the first draft of the agreement last week is on the conscience of Republican MPs.
Since Democrats have come to the conclusion that for some “toxic” assets of companies in difficulty, the government will only guarantee, but will not buy them back, there is a belief that the deadlock is inflamed.
In an effort to reconcile conflicting views in Congress, a provision was added that the government would be able to introduce new fees to help it recover its deposit if it would have to take over losses as a result of the program for five years.
The new plan envisages a first deposit of $250 billion, to which an additional $100 billion will be added if the president deems it necessary.
An additional $350 billion is expected to be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will get shares in the rescued companies, which will pay him dividends in case of profit, and which he will be able to resell when it is over.
The federal government will have the option of delaying the procedures for the seizure of real estate associated with the loans concerned by the plan, as well as setting limits on the amount of assessment and compensation paid to managers of affected companies.
Plan makers would like to submit it to a vote in the House of Representatives today and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all the efforts, it is not yet certain whether their plan will have a green one.
Yesterday, voices continued to rise against the project in both the Republican and Democratic camps.
“It’s absolutely clear that Washington can’t hear you,” Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, told voters.
“Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
Earning money from taxpayers is not a solution.”
Democratic Rep. Brad Sherman, the moderator of a group of congressmen dubbed the "Committee of Skeptics", presents the whole thing differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred distinguished professors of economics, including three Nobel laureates, wrote to us: we ask Congress not to rush too fast and carefully examine which way to go," he said.
At the same time, it has been reaffirmed in Europe that this crisis is a global crisis.
At the end of the extraordinary meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the Fortis banking group for <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>11.2 billion ($16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was withdrawing from the purchase of its competitor, which is on the verge of collapse since it lost <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2 billion (US$2.9 billion) to the state in the wake of a crisis of risks.
Fortis employs 85,000 people, is among the top 20 European banks and among the top ten insurers.
