Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of Socially Engaged Icons
His beauty with azure eyes for a long time represented his trump, according to other weaknesses.
Did this American actor come out with a charming smile from narcissism?
Yes and no.
The shyness, sensitivity and unwavering talent that were his own also distanced him from the power category that produces true stars.
But what a long-distance runner he was!
Paul Newman died Friday at the age of 83 on his Connecticut ranch from lung cancer and remains one of the last icons of the fat years of American cinema.
Less spectacular than Brando, who was similar to him and had long been a rival to him on the screen, Newman was a more cautious actor, certainly more fragile, but also an apostle of freedom and the disintegration of dramatic conventions.
Mixed blood often gives birth to beautiful children.
Born in Ohio in 1925, his father was a German Jew and his mother was of Hungarian descent.
From these European roots was born one of the famous faces of the American dream.
No excessive ego, which is the last sign of quality.
Because in it, the whole country looked in love with self-made mana, a warrior in the Pacific War, wounded in battle, who in the early 1950s studied acting at Yale, then visited New York's Actor's Studio and celebrated triumphs in theater, television, and film.
The same man who fought for civil rights was also a car racer who placed second at the 24 hour race at Le Mans in 1979, and at the same time a sexual symbol, despite having formed a model couple with actress Joanne Woodward since 1958.
With it also go the shadows of this hidden, discreet, socially engaged stars, allergic to the hustle and bustle of their own show business, which will forever remain to a certain extent mysterious.
A decent man, in the most noble sense of the word.
Paul Newman’s departure this weekend caused dizziness for film lovers, as his big roles competed together on a black canvas of memories.
After him, more than half a century of the ever-changing American seventh art parade.
A charming cowboy from Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969), a young man who rejects his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in The Cat on the Hot Roof, a 1958 adaptation of Tennessee Williams.
From a less ancient past (1990), we remember his sensitive Mr. Bridge, troubled at an advanced age by a marriage that did not meet all expectations.
So many other Paul Newmans have gone down in history.
Boxer Rocky Graziano, a perverted, violent, unforgettable offender from Robert Wise's Somebody Up There Likes Me, a role intended for James Dean, taken over after his death, which in 1956 brought Newman to the real world.
A sympathetic gangster in the absolutely great The Sting, an Oscar for Best Picture in 1973.
A bitter and vindictive billiards player in Robert Rossen's The Hustler (1961), the same character portrayed in Martin Scorsese's The Color of Money, which earned him the only Oscar out of seven nominations in 1987.
That face wandering ages, it was him.
And him again.
In his professional career, different epochs compete together.
Young people know him mainly thanks to the iconic Slap Shot by George Roy Hill (1977) from the role of Reggie Dunlop, an unconventional hockey coach.
Fans reunited with him in 1994 in The Hudsucker Proxy of the Coen Brothers.
He ended his career as the godfather of the Irish mafia in Road to Perdition by Sam Mendes in 2003.
Unlike several film legends who left the craft relatively soon, Newman remained in the industry for a long time, although he condemned Hollywood with its gilding, showcasing, and concessions.
The French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier considered him, not without humor, "a living challenge of underplaying", judging that in his performances he pushed too much on the saw.
For the beautiful Paul Newman, to whom the roles came as on trays, the profession was not always so tender.
However, the first lovers played less often than the outsiders: neurotics, alcoholics, lumps and despairers, whose fall and rebellions were reflected in his perfect features.
As a director, Newman revealed little-known aspects of his shy sensibility.
His 1968 film Rachel, based on the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence, starring his wife Joanne Woodward, presents a sensitive female portrait full of melancholy.
In 1984, he dedicated Harry and Son to his son Scott, whom he lost to overdose, a work full of shame and sadness.
In a homage to Newman yesterday, his great friend and former comrade Robert Redford (who played together in The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) sadly declared, "His presence has made my life and this country better."
Generosity, love of life, these are the main characteristics of the deceased actor.
In addition to his legendary career, there is also a great fighter for civil rights, ecology, independent film, opponent of the decline of Hollywood.
We were used to seeing his image on bottles of wine vinegar, sauces, cookies and other foods, which might have seemed quite tasteless to us, although at first it was a gag.
However, the profits from the sale went to the account of his Foundation for Difficult Childhood.
Newman thus, rather than let himself be swayed by fame, engaged in society until the last moment.
He left a letter to his five daughters containing the following sentences: "Always and to the end, your father was grateful to his happy planet.
I was honored to be here.”
And for us, it was an honor to be able to follow the path of such a bright and generous American artist.
And besides, after all, a model citizen.
