The psychology of trumps: why do we spend more money?
At auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overestimate the goods.
The neurological and economic foundations of this well-known—and seemingly irrational—behavior were revealed to researchers in the field of neurology and economics at the University of New York.
According to their study, published in the journal Science, people don’t want to lag behind in an eBay auction contest, so they’d rather pay too much.
With the help of an experimental auction, the research tried to map the scheme of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers bet, the other group participated in a play auction, with the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method examining the active brain areas of the subjects.
In both games, participants could win money, but in the auction game, an important element of which is to beat the other side, the whole under the cerebral cortex, called the striatum, began to work intensely during the loss.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region plays a role in the "self-replacement" mechanism of the nervous system.
According to the researchers, the price tightening can therefore be explained by trying to avoid a sharp reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, members of the research team from the ranks of economists conducted a financial cross-sectional survey.
Under different conditions, three groups were bidding against one partner.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product was, and they made bets.
Members of the other group were also promised that if they came out victorious, they would receive another $15 in reward.
The third group, on the contrary, received $ 15 before the auction, but in the event of a loss, its members also lost this money.
The difference between the two groups was, therefore, that one group emphasized victory and the other group emphasized defeat.
However, members of the group playing "against the loss" were willing to go higher than in the control and "winning" group, which confirms the hypothesis of neurologists.
“These results cannot be derived from any previously existing economic theory.
These have so far explained the phenomena observable during auctions of joys of victory and avoidance of risk.
Only neurological imaging methods helped us to resolve the contradiction between these two theories so that we have now reached a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when to seek a doctor?
About half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary, this chronic liver disease is among the leading causes of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand of them are treated. The reason for this is that patients often do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is a summary name for infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
In their symptoms there are many similarities, characteristic is inflammation of the liver and jaundice, but the causes of the disease and the diseases caused by them differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, depending on the origins of the disease, spread in two main ways: hepatitis type A and E of the digestive system (for example, infected food, water), hepatitis type B, C, D and other viruses of blood and body fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
Travellers should in any case be protected by vaccination against viruses A and B, there is no type C vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating an infected meal, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal discomfort, urge to vomit.
After that, a yellowing, lightening of the stool and darkening of the urine is formed on the skin and on the whites of the eyes. Treatment can take two to three weeks.
Every year, a million people worldwide die of a more serious type of the disease, liver cancer and cirrhosis of the liver caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that, according to estimates, only one in ten infected people is treated with medication.
