Smart car mimics the flight of a camel
What, then, would be the best method of developing technologies capable of preventing collisions, if not imitation of obstacle detectors occurring in the world of nature?
In the case of bees, for example.
The initial strategic idea of the surprising project, presented at the Japanese CEATEC fair, was inspired by the engineers from Nissan. It was about how to build a new generation of systems to prevent collisions.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has designed the BR23C biomimetic robotic steering system, a robotic mini-car that is equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the ultimate goal of helping to create a system that can eliminate all collisions.
“During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of an oval shape, which is actually very similar to our safety protective packaging,” Kazuhiro Doi, the brand’s chief technology PR and R&D officer, explained at the show.
An important role is played by the folded eyes, which allow the bees to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the folded eye, engineers came up with the idea of a laser rangefinder.
It identifies obstacles at a distance of up to 2 meters from the BR23C in a 180-degree field of view, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately turns into an operation aimed at preventing a collision.
The obstacle is captured within a fraction of a second, then the robotized car begins to mimic the movements of the bee and by turning the wheels to the extent necessary to prevent a collision, it immediately changes direction.
Unlike any existing system, this maneuver is done in a completely instinctive way.
“If this were not the case, a robot car would not be able to respond quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshijuki Ando, head of the Mobility Laboratory and Robotic Car Project.
It must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology fits the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the protective packaging, inside which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
This process should not take longer than a blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction in which the wheels can be rotated.
Instead of the endless possibilities offered to bees when avoiding, in the case of a robot car, only the possibility of rotational movement, acceleration and deceleration was applied.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, meaning they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion variants.
According to Ando, an instinctive, intelligent response is important, not the processing ability, let alone the storage of data.
This mechanism must process and respond only to a few incoming signals per second.
There is no need to store and respond to them using intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it constantly uses only a few kilobytes of memory.
It does not need a memory with giga- or megabyte capacity.
This is the first step in the development of technology for immediate avoidance that, according to Nissan’s estimates, could reach mass-produced vehicles in ten years.
Another option may be to connect the unit to the GPS satellite navigation system, which, after avoiding obstacles in the way, would lead the motorist to the specified final destination.
