MP3 Players Accused of Exposing Hearing to Risk
Listening to loud music for an extended period of time and using portable music devices such as Mp3 players can cause permanent hearing loss.
According to today's announcement by the European Commission, which quotes the opinion of the Scientific Committee on Health Risks recently raised and identified (Csrseri) EU in an official report published in Brussels.
“From this scientific view, it follows that 5-10% of those who listen to music using portable music devices for at least five years, more than an hour a week, and keep the device at high volumes, risk permanent hearing loss.”
“I’m concerned that so many young people who use often portable musical devices and mobile phones at high acoustic levels may unknowingly damage their hearing in an irreversible way,” Kuneva said.
"From scientific findings - continues the leader - there is a clear risk and there is a need to react quickly.
The most important thing is that we must encourage consumers and make this information public.
We need to continue to re-examine existing control systems in the light of this scientific finding to become fully effective and to keep up with the new technology.”
Brussels has asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine this problem in view of the high use of portable musical instruments and the increasing number of young people exposed to noise of this origin.
"Scientists confirm that there is a need to be concerned and the European Commission will now examine together with the other members and parties who raised the problem what measures could possibly be introduced to better protect children and young people from exposure to noise, the source of which is the noise."
Currently, there is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable musical instruments to 100 dB, but there are growing concerns about hearing damage that may be caused by excessive exposure to similar forms of noise.
It is possible to greatly limit these damages by looking for solutions such as reducing the level and duration of exposure.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee states that when users of portable music devices use loud music (more than 89 decibels) for only five hours per week, they will exceed the currently valid limits corresponding to the maximum permissible noise at the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for a long time run the risk of permanent hearing loss after five years.
This problem should affect 5-10% of users of such devices and their quantity can be counted between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
