Krugman is a 55-year-old New Yorker who teaches at Priceton University and is a well-known editor of the New York Times.
Krugman is one of the most important critics of the Bush administration’s foreign, economic and political moves.
A few months after the September 2001 attacks, in the days Enron crashed, Krugman predicted in a New York Times commentary that the second event would be, in terms of consequences for U.S. history, far more important than the first.
A prediction that caused a lot of controversy and that was refuted for years, but proved to be accurate.
"I'm surprised and shocked at how quickly collapses like Enron and Worldcom have disappeared from public interest," Krugman said in a statement.
According to Lorenzo Biniho Smaghi of the Executive Committee of the European Central Bank, Krugman is “an economist of great importance” but also a popularizer who has “a very aggressive style, especially critical of the excesses of the Bush liberal administration.”
Open Office, we have here the third edition of the "anti-Microsoft" package
It’s Open Office.org 3.0, an open source personal production package aimed at reaching more and more users, from home to office, from professionals to public administration, as a free alternative to the more familiar Microsoft Office.
After about a year of volunteer work, controlled by SUN Microsystem, the new Open Office is shown to the general public with a variety of novelties: to the welcome screen and to the revised and improved opening window are added another, much more significant, such as the compatibility for the operating system Apple Mac OS X and the support of the new format ISO 1.2.
Emphasis is also placed on collaboration with the Office 2007 package, Open Office is able to open the document with the new Microsoft extension (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx).
Interesting are the special features of some models, such as what allows you to reduce the size of your PowerPoint presentation, useful for example for transferring electronically, or the ability to transfer a PDF folder to a graphical model and maintain the original appearance of the page.
Still from this point of view, we can create documents "PDF hybrids" that resemble typical graphics of the Adobe format and have the properties of a table processor or text program.
Collaboration is an element that has received many improvements within application programs: in Excel, it is possible to work together between different users and avoid conflicts on changes, in the text program, each employee is assigned one color to the comments to be clearer identification in the revision phase.
Some companies are also working on transferring some Open Office features to the Web (on the cloud), and in the coming weeks, they should reset the final result.
The Italian version can be downloaded at http://en.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html, has been added to the English version, which has been on the mirror since Friday.
In addition to Windows and Mac OS, as usual, the package is also available for the Linux operating system.
Also, the installation cd can be sent home or to the workplace on request.
And while the theme of gratuitousness can be a drag on the expansion in households, it is the business area of Open Office that the package bets a lot, and can already count on a variety of projects implemented in public administration and in schools.
And there is no shortage of training, consultation and assistance services ideal for small and medium-sized companies, which could open up business perspectives.
Open Office consists of five main models: Writer, for video writing replacing Word; Calc is a spreadsheet processor that aims to replace Excel; Impress for PowerPoint-like presentations; Dbase, as in the case of more famous Access, is a program that allows you to work on databases; Draw, finally, is a graphical model.
The goal for 2008 is to achieve 5 million downloads, and considering that we are at almost 3 million and 600,000 today, with the release of a new version it is possible that this expected number can be exceeded.
