Students victims of expensive rents - up to 900 euros per room
The rental market for university students does not know the crisis.
According to the latest research by Sunia, unions for tenants, renting a single room can cost a student in Milan up to 900 euros, in Florence 700, in Naples 650, in Rome 600.
"Jew has already reached such dimensions that entire layers of students have lost the right to study because of the overall too high prices that their families would have to bear," explains the head of the Sunia studios' office, Laura Mariani, in this city, a large demand from the students, which has distorted the market.
In most cases, the rental offer contains several offences: contracts free of charge, unregistered, without limited rental, and related sub-leasing.
For Sunji, an exceptional intervention is needed, which could regulate prices thanks to the tax revision.
If we look at the details of the research, we will see that in Milan, in the Brianza area, one bed is needed for about 450 euros, a single room is paid from a minimum price of 650 (the Bande Nere area) through the average value of 800 (the Lambiate, Udine and Fiera area) to a maximum of 900 (in the Vittoria area).
In Florence, one bed costs an average of 350/400 euros, one room about 700.
In Bologna, where students concentrate in areas close to the university, it takes 250/280 euros per bed in a double room, from 370 to 500 in a single room.
In Rome in the central university zones (San Lorenzo, piazza Bologna) they want about 600 euros per single room, 450 beds in a double.
The values are slightly lower (550 euros per single) in areas close to other universities (Ostiense and Cinecitt<0xC3><0xA0>).
We will only save if we move to the peripheral areas: 300 euros per bed and 450 for a single room zones Prenestina, Centocelle and the like.
In Naples it is necessary for a bed 300/450 euros, for a room from 400 to 600 euros, with the highest prices in the zones Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei.
In Bar they want 250/350 euros for a bed, at least 350 for a single room.
In smaller cities, prices are definitely lower, but they have greater impact on the economy of citizens.
In cities like Perugia, where rent is the most common phenomenon for students from countries outside the European Union, one more anomaly is finally recorded: an increase of about 25-30% of the fee they want for foreign students, compared to the Italian ones.
Farewell to the old cinema Paradiso, cities destroy historic halls
Cinematographic historical halls are closing in favor of Multiplex.
"A city without cinema is like a blind man, like a face without eyes."
The image offered by director Giuseppe Tornator successfully documents what is happening in large Italian city centers, but also in rural towns.
The process of restricting cinemas, the birth of large multi-sales in the suburbs, and the subsequent demise of mono-sales in the central zones of cities, is one of the events that seem to be inevitable and irreversible, but also has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
“It’s as if we’ve lost a friend, a friend, with whom we shared a piece of the road and a lot of emotions,” says the director of the New Cinema Paradiso, a film that won a lifetime Oscar for Tornator and a grand prize in Cannes.
The values obtained by Anec, the main association of operators, speak clearly: in the last five years, the doors of 316 cinemas of the traditional type have closed, and the highest bill paid mainly halls in the most important cities: about 10 less in Florence, about 9 in Milan, about 6 in Milan, about Neapoli
Among the regions most affected by the closures is Emilia-Romagna, with a loss of 82 cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And proof that the first responsible for their disappearance is the emergence of multiplex, it is these three Italian regions that registered the highest number of new cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"Italian approach has developed in an irrational way," says Paolo Protti, president of Anecu, "it is useful to create new structures, but it would be necessary to guarantee that those already existing will survive, because when one cinema in the city closes, not all of its visitors are willing to move to multiplex.
Not to mention the insufficient subsidy to the fund for the benefit of the operators: the previous public debt is about 10 million euros.
From a moral and ethical point of view, it is a shame that the government does not respect existing laws.
Between <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>16 million and <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>18 million per year would be needed to support the sector.”
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city to be concerned about closures and which decided to find a way out by signing a protocol between the municipalities and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy to protect and promote small cinemas both in the historical centers and in the suburbs.
Among the planned norms are steps of tax relief in favour of operators and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the zone with limited transport and will have special prices to stop and in some car parks.
“I like this initiative,” says Giuseppe Tornatore, “and I hope that other cities will follow Bologna’s example by introducing other measures.”
However, it is certain that in order to resist the great power of multiplex, traditional halls must improve the quality of sound and image, because today’s audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a topic that has always been important: the closure of the Super cinema in Bagheria, instead of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to establish the "New Cinema Paradiso", which I have been thinking about for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years, and when I walk in front of the already closed Rialta or Quirinale in the Rue Nazionale, where I have shared so many emotions that I do not have to look at the inscriptions blackened with dust, I turn to the other side.
Connection between politics and mafia group 'ndrangheta, mayor Gioie Tauro in prison
