Other interrogations ordered against Dal Torrion, the prosecutors write, revealed "a willingness to shift the claims of an entrepreneur, a representative of some larger group very close, as is generally known, to Piromalli and to adapt the public administration's choices to the interests of the mafia group."
When the energy is born from the waves, the big ones come into play.
It is an infinite deposit that covers more than 70% of the earth’s surface and is now being discovered by the world’s major energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides, outflows are the new sources of inexhaustible energy on which the eyes of giants like Chevron, who is now trying to reach out to these sources, have clung.
The possibility of generating energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for more than a hundred years, and in the 1970s, in the context of the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell around 1980, the idea of using marine energy went away. But now the environmental organizations and the new rise in oil prices have given the sector a new impetus.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London in 2007 stated that about 15 percent of the world’s electricity consumption could be covered by the use of sea waves.
That would be twice the amount of energy that is currently produced in nuclear power plants.
In addition, there are currents and tides and outflows.
The giants are attacking.
The company that invested in marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 agreed to build the facility in northern Portugal.
When this plan was announced, it looked like a huge revolutionary step.
After two years of betting on marine energy, more and more companies are betting on marine energy rather than traditional energy.
“Chevron is studying ocean energy technology,” said a spokesman for a company linked to the U.S. oil giant in the Wall Street Journal’s economic daily newspaper, “and is thinking about the possibility of working with us.”
The cooperation we are considering is about obtaining the authorization from the U.S. Energy Commission, which is necessary for the launch of the project on the use of marine energy in Alaska.
We cannot underestimate this signal, especially considering that it is in Alaska that the US continues to extract oil and President Bush has recently come up with a plan for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey are monitoring the marine energy footprint, and the amounts invested so far, although not in detail known, show growing interest, according to observers.
